article.description: Chamique Holdsclaw hit a 15-foot jumper with 2.4 seconds remaining to give the Washington Mystics a 62-60 victory over the New York Liberty and their first home victory of the season.
article.headline: Liberty fall in game in College Park
article.linkText: Holdsclaw's late bucket lifts Mystics to first 'home' win
article.story:
COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- The game-winning shot gave Chamique Holdsclaw a familiar feeling.

Holdsclaw hit a 15-foot jumper with 2.4 seconds remaining to give the Washington Mystics a 62-60 victory over the New York Liberty and their first home victory of the season.

"I was having deja vu," Holdsclaw said. "I hit that same shot
from the same place against New York a couple years ago at the
Garden. So I thought: 'I know it's coming to me and if I get
daylight just put it up.' I'm just glad it went in."

Liberty coach Richie Adubato could only credit Holdsclaw.

"Crystal Robinson is one of the best defenders in the league,
Holdsclaw just made an unbelievable shot," Adubato said.

The Mystics had lost eight in a row at home, dating back to last
season. The home fans were somewhat deprived, however, as the game
was played at the University of Maryland's Comcast Center to
accommodate a Madonna concert Sunday night at MCI Center.

"I didn't want to come out here because I'm very happy down at
that MCI," Adubato quipped. "I'm very superstitious and it's been
a good place for us to play, and now we come out here and get a
loss."

The Mystics last regular-season home victory over New York was
four years ago.

Chasity Melvin led the Mystics with 15 points, seven rebounds
and two blocks. Holdsclaw finished with 14 points and 14 rebounds.

"Chasity said she needs to touch the ball to help us, and she
touched it tonight," Mystics coach Michael Adams.

Melvin came off the bench to make six of eight shots.

"Hopefully, this will get us to turn the corner," Adams said.

After Holdsclaw's winning shot, Stacey Dales-Schuman blocked a
shot by Vickie Johnson as the final horn sounded.

"We should have never been in that position," Robinson said.
"Their 18 offensive rebounds really killed us. We would have won
that game easy if we had rebounded better."

The Mystics, who got at least one rebound from everyone who
played, outrebounded the Liberty, 40-26.

"My team just played relentless," Holsdclaw said. "We crushed
them on the boards. As a key player on your team, when your shot's
not working, you have to do something else, so I tried to create for
other people and just rebound the basketball.

"I think I wound up with 14 rebounds. I'll take that with a
win."

Becky Hammon and Robinson scored 12 points apiece for New York.
Johnson added 11. Hammon's 3-pointer with 8.3 seconds left tied the
score at 60.

"I didn't even think about it," Hammon said. "It was a normal
out-of-bounds play we run in practice all the time. We shouldn't
have been in that position."

She also had a three-point play over Tamicha Jackson that pulled
the Liberty to 54-50 with 1:37 remaining. Robinson's two free
throws got New York to 54-52 with 47 seconds left.

The teams traded big shots down the stretch, starting with a
jump shot by Holdsclaw that put Washington ahead 56-52 with 34
seconds left.

Robinson came right back with a 3-pointer to cut the lead to one
with 26 seconds left.

Dales-Schuman put Washington up 60-57 with two free throws,
but Hammon tied it moments later.

The Mystics led 48-41 with 6:07 left after Coco Miller made two
buckets and Melvin sank a hook and converted a three-point play.
